1
00:00:32,041 --> 00:00:33,791
[groaning]

2
00:00:39,583 --> 00:00:41,916
♪

3
00:00:43,041 --> 00:00:44,291
[gasps]

4
00:00:45,541 --> 00:00:46,708
[SUGIMOTO]
Blue eyes.

5
00:00:48,416 --> 00:00:51,166
Hold on.
Do you know what this is?

6
00:00:53,333 --> 00:00:55,750
♪

7
00:00:57,208 --> 00:00:58,333
Is that...

8
00:00:58,416 --> 00:01:01,083
That's the makiri
I made for Asirpa.

9
00:01:02,125 --> 00:01:04,875
How did it end up with you?

10
00:01:04,958 --> 00:01:06,500
[SUGIMOTO]
So it's true.

11
00:01:07,541 --> 00:01:09,208
Just as Asirpa feared.

12
00:01:09,291 --> 00:01:12,208
Nopperabo really is her father.

13
00:01:13,291 --> 00:01:14,708
Is she...

14
00:01:14,791 --> 00:01:16,416
Where is she? Is she here?

15
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:17,500
[SUGIMOTO]
Come on.

16
00:01:17,583 --> 00:01:19,541
You're telling me everything.

17
00:01:19,625 --> 00:01:21,166
If you want to know
where the gold is,

18
00:01:21,250 --> 00:01:23,458
then bring Asirpa to me now.

19
00:01:23,541 --> 00:01:25,291
I'll only tell my daughter.

20
00:01:30,291 --> 00:01:32,916
[INUDOU] Takeaki Enomoto
is now a viscount!

21
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:34,750
And what are you, Hijikata,

22
00:01:34,833 --> 00:01:37,583
but a spent, old,
wrinkled fugitive.

23
00:01:37,666 --> 00:01:41,000
If you'd just agreed to join
the new Meiji government army.

24
00:01:43,333 --> 00:01:45,000
Then maybe you wouldn't have
had to spend

25
00:01:45,083 --> 00:01:47,416
over 30 years
of your life in chains!

26
00:01:47,500 --> 00:01:48,500
[grunts]

27
00:01:50,916 --> 00:01:52,375
Beg for your life.

28
00:01:52,458 --> 00:01:55,708
The only thing that'll save you
now is your obedience.

29
00:01:55,791 --> 00:01:59,166
You can start by polishing
my boots every day.

30
00:02:00,333 --> 00:02:02,083
So after all these years,

31
00:02:02,166 --> 00:02:04,416
you're still trying to get me
to join the Meiji government

32
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:05,916
like you always have.

33
00:02:08,500 --> 00:02:10,500
You repaid the loyalty
of the Tokugawas

34
00:02:10,583 --> 00:02:13,000
with hatred,
contempt, and betrayal.

35
00:02:13,083 --> 00:02:14,750
What gives you the right
to demand loyalty

36
00:02:14,833 --> 00:02:18,375
after so brazenly demonstrating
that you have none of your own?

37
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:22,291
Your fear is painted
all over your face,

38
00:02:22,375 --> 00:02:24,375
and nothing frightens you
more than the soldiers

39
00:02:24,458 --> 00:02:27,208
of the old shogunate
who became martyrs.

40
00:02:29,250 --> 00:02:31,291
In order to justify
your brother's death

41
00:02:31,375 --> 00:02:33,375
during the Battle of Hakodate,

42
00:02:33,458 --> 00:02:36,708
and your own
miserable existence,

43
00:02:36,791 --> 00:02:38,833
you needed to lock me away.

44
00:02:38,916 --> 00:02:41,791
Until I became like you.

45
00:02:43,750 --> 00:02:47,291
So when that moment came,
the revenge of Shirosuke Inudou

46
00:02:47,375 --> 00:02:49,166
would finally be complete.

47
00:02:50,458 --> 00:02:51,708
You could never bear the fact

48
00:02:51,791 --> 00:02:53,708
that a peasant
from the countryside like me

49
00:02:53,791 --> 00:02:55,791
was more loyal than the samurai.

50
00:02:55,875 --> 00:02:58,333
That doesn't make sense
in your small-minded view

51
00:02:58,416 --> 00:03:00,541
of the world
and the way things should work.

52
00:03:00,625 --> 00:03:02,458
Isn't that right, Inudou?

53
00:03:02,541 --> 00:03:04,125
Shut up.

54
00:03:04,208 --> 00:03:06,250
I'll break you even if it means
ripping you limb from limb.

55
00:03:08,208 --> 00:03:09,583
[grunts]

56
00:03:09,666 --> 00:03:10,583
[groans]

57
00:03:20,083 --> 00:03:22,541
I'm still strong enough
to take you alive.

58
00:03:22,625 --> 00:03:24,250
Better remember that, old man.

59
00:03:24,333 --> 00:03:25,458
[groaning]

60
00:03:25,541 --> 00:03:27,416
[grunts]

61
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:28,791
[groaning]

62
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:40,083
[exhales sharply]

63
00:03:43,541 --> 00:03:44,916
Go on.

64
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:46,958
Do it, last of the samurai.

65
00:03:57,208 --> 00:03:59,833
[SUGIMOTO] You're going to
tell me where the gold is.

66
00:03:59,916 --> 00:04:01,916
But first, there's something

67
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,083
I've wanted to say to you
for a while now.

68
00:04:05,833 --> 00:04:08,416
To tell you the truth,
the last thing

69
00:04:08,500 --> 00:04:10,125
I want is for Asirpa to see you.

70
00:04:11,250 --> 00:04:13,083
She's anxious.

71
00:04:13,166 --> 00:04:15,333
Terrified that the man
who killed the Ainu

72
00:04:15,416 --> 00:04:16,458
and stole their gold

73
00:04:16,541 --> 00:04:19,083
might actually be
her own father.

74
00:04:19,166 --> 00:04:20,500
Why did you tell
Hijikata the name

75
00:04:20,583 --> 00:04:22,041
"Asuko Kochoube"?

76
00:04:23,458 --> 00:04:25,375
Why did you risk getting
Asirpa involved?

77
00:04:27,083 --> 00:04:29,333
I'm entrusting her
with the future.

78
00:04:29,416 --> 00:04:31,500
I left her
in those mountains to learn.

79
00:04:31,583 --> 00:04:34,333
I wanted her to grow up
fighting as a guerrilla.

80
00:04:34,416 --> 00:04:38,708
One day, my daughter will be
the leader of the Ainu people.

81
00:04:38,791 --> 00:04:40,583
Lead the Ainu?

82
00:04:40,666 --> 00:04:42,708
So that's what you want?

83
00:04:42,791 --> 00:04:44,583
To use your own daughter
as some pawn

84
00:04:44,666 --> 00:04:47,083
in the Ainu
independence movement?

85
00:04:47,166 --> 00:04:50,208
Are you trying to turn her into
some kind of Ainu Joan of Arc?

86
00:04:50,291 --> 00:04:52,250
[PRISONERS clamoring]

87
00:04:52,333 --> 00:04:53,750
[TSURUMI]
Where you goin', boys?

88
00:04:53,833 --> 00:04:55,791
The fun's not over quite yet.

89
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,416
Here's a present from
Lieutenant General Arisaka!

90
00:05:00,500 --> 00:05:01,875
[laughing menacingly]

91
00:05:02,875 --> 00:05:04,125
You really want your daughter

92
00:05:04,208 --> 00:05:06,500
to become a murderer
like you and me?!

93
00:05:06,583 --> 00:05:09,250
I don't care that
what you're doing is right!

94
00:05:09,333 --> 00:05:11,333
I get that somebody
has to fight for this!

95
00:05:11,416 --> 00:05:12,500
But it doesn't...

96
00:05:13,625 --> 00:05:16,291
There's no reason
it has to be her.

97
00:05:16,375 --> 00:05:19,416
I want Asirpa to spend her days
hunting deer in the mountains,

98
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:20,958
eating their brains.

99
00:05:21,041 --> 00:05:23,416
Turning them into chitatap
and saying "hinna, hinna"

100
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:24,916
until she's old and gray!

101
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,625
♪

102
00:05:27,708 --> 00:05:29,291
How interesting.

103
00:05:29,375 --> 00:05:33,000
She seems to have had
quite an effect on you, Sisam.

104
00:05:33,083 --> 00:05:35,125
[SUGIMOTO exhales]

105
00:05:35,208 --> 00:05:36,125
Huh?

106
00:05:39,916 --> 00:05:42,000
[NOPPERABO]
I know that kimono.

107
00:05:44,666 --> 00:05:46,166
[gasps]

108
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:48,250
[INKARMAT]
A prisoner uniform.

109
00:05:48,333 --> 00:05:49,916
And is that...

110
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:51,458
Hey, Asirpa!

111
00:05:51,541 --> 00:05:53,625
You need to get up here!

112
00:05:53,708 --> 00:05:54,583
[gasps]

113
00:05:57,083 --> 00:05:58,750
Okay, can you see her?

114
00:06:00,041 --> 00:06:01,291
Inkarmat.

115
00:06:04,500 --> 00:06:07,666
Nopperabo has to be
somewhere close by. Find him.

116
00:06:09,666 --> 00:06:10,916
Look over there.

117
00:06:17,958 --> 00:06:20,000
♪

118
00:06:23,125 --> 00:06:24,750
[ASIRPA]
Aca.

119
00:06:24,833 --> 00:06:27,500
It's a red Kimun Kamuy.

120
00:06:27,583 --> 00:06:30,416
[NOPPERABO]
Asirpa, I know you can do this.

121
00:06:30,500 --> 00:06:32,208
[gasps]

122
00:06:32,291 --> 00:06:33,416
Aca?

123
00:06:35,916 --> 00:06:37,000
-[bear approaching]
-Hmm?

124
00:06:37,083 --> 00:06:37,958
[gasps]

125
00:06:39,875 --> 00:06:41,750
[growling]

126
00:06:41,833 --> 00:06:42,666
[gasps]

127
00:06:46,416 --> 00:06:47,833
[groaning]

128
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,458
♪

129
00:06:55,666 --> 00:06:57,000
[panting]

130
00:07:04,666 --> 00:07:06,250
[heavy breathing]

131
00:07:07,958 --> 00:07:09,166
Guess the poison got it.

132
00:07:10,583 --> 00:07:12,041
[NOPPERABO]
Well done, Asirpa.

133
00:07:12,125 --> 00:07:14,625
You didn't get scared
and your moves were precise.

134
00:07:17,916 --> 00:07:20,000
Still such a wee little thing.

135
00:07:20,083 --> 00:07:23,583
And already you've fought
and defeated a great bear.

136
00:07:23,666 --> 00:07:24,666
[grunting]

137
00:07:24,750 --> 00:07:26,875
[laughs]
I'm sorry.

138
00:07:31,083 --> 00:07:32,875
I'm so proud of you.

139
00:07:32,958 --> 00:07:34,416
Your mustache stinks.

140
00:07:36,125 --> 00:07:37,791
[grunts]

141
00:07:37,875 --> 00:07:39,291
Asirpa.

142
00:07:39,375 --> 00:07:41,000
My fearless daughter.

143
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:44,750
You are the future
of the Ainu now.

144
00:07:48,583 --> 00:07:50,416
Well? Tell us.

145
00:07:50,500 --> 00:07:52,041
Do you think that's your father?

146
00:07:53,666 --> 00:07:54,791
Is it him?

147
00:07:57,083 --> 00:07:58,750
It's aca.

148
00:07:58,833 --> 00:08:01,000
[KIRORANKE] You're absolutely
sure it's Wilk?

149
00:08:01,083 --> 00:08:03,083
Is she okay?

150
00:08:03,166 --> 00:08:04,458
What's her expression?

151
00:08:04,541 --> 00:08:06,500
♪

152
00:08:14,666 --> 00:08:16,416
[ASIRPA]
Aca.

153
00:08:16,500 --> 00:08:17,583
Why?

154
00:08:26,208 --> 00:08:29,375
Tell her I wasn't the one
who killed the Ainu.

155
00:08:29,458 --> 00:08:31,291
Huh?

156
00:08:31,375 --> 00:08:33,166
I want her to know that.

157
00:08:33,250 --> 00:08:34,583
-The gold--
-[gunshot]

158
00:08:41,375 --> 00:08:43,041
Wilk was just shot in the head!

159
00:08:43,125 --> 00:08:44,041
[BOTH gasp]

160
00:08:45,583 --> 00:08:47,583
[SUGIMOTO grunts]

161
00:08:47,666 --> 00:08:48,583
[gunshot]

162
00:09:00,916 --> 00:09:04,625
Sugimoto!

163
00:09:06,375 --> 00:09:08,458
♪

164
00:09:11,625 --> 00:09:13,083
[INKARMAT]
Run, Asirpa.

165
00:09:13,166 --> 00:09:15,125
You have to get out of here.

166
00:09:15,208 --> 00:09:17,625
You're in more danger
than you can imagine.

167
00:09:17,708 --> 00:09:21,500
The only key to the mystery
of the gold is in you now.

168
00:09:21,583 --> 00:09:23,875
Soon they'll all be killing
each other over you.

169
00:09:26,500 --> 00:09:27,833
[panting]

170
00:09:30,041 --> 00:09:31,083
-[rustling]
-Huh?

171
00:09:36,291 --> 00:09:38,208
Aca! Sugimoto!

172
00:09:38,291 --> 00:09:39,583
-Let go of me!
-It's over!

173
00:09:39,666 --> 00:09:40,666
-They're gone.
-Put me down!

174
00:09:40,750 --> 00:09:41,833
We're leaving right now.

175
00:09:41,916 --> 00:09:43,000
That's not true!

176
00:09:43,083 --> 00:09:44,791
I won't leave them!

177
00:09:44,875 --> 00:09:46,166
Let me go!

178
00:09:46,250 --> 00:09:47,958
-They're just right over there!
-You can't go.

179
00:09:48,041 --> 00:09:50,041
Whoever shot them
is still close by!

180
00:09:50,125 --> 00:09:51,875
-[ASIRPA] Aca!
-Sugimoto?

181
00:09:51,958 --> 00:09:53,333
Seriously?

182
00:09:53,416 --> 00:09:55,291
-What do we do?
-[sighs]

183
00:09:56,666 --> 00:09:58,083
I got it.

184
00:09:58,166 --> 00:09:59,875
You stay close to Asirpa.

185
00:09:59,958 --> 00:10:01,500
Wait by the spare ship!

186
00:10:01,583 --> 00:10:02,583
Tanigaki Nispa!

187
00:10:02,666 --> 00:10:03,916
Don't go out there!

188
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,250
It's too dangerous!

189
00:10:06,333 --> 00:10:08,083
[grunting]

190
00:10:10,833 --> 00:10:12,208
[gunshot]

191
00:10:16,083 --> 00:10:18,083
[OGATA] A little further
to the left, huh?

192
00:10:21,041 --> 00:10:22,708
[grunting]

193
00:10:26,875 --> 00:10:27,875
[groans]

194
00:10:28,916 --> 00:10:29,833
[grunts]

195
00:10:29,916 --> 00:10:31,875
That goddamn Matagi.

196
00:10:31,958 --> 00:10:33,166
[grunting]

197
00:10:34,875 --> 00:10:37,208
[panting]

198
00:10:37,291 --> 00:10:39,083
♪

199
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:50,916
[TANIGAKI panting]

200
00:11:02,041 --> 00:11:03,416
Inkarmat!

201
00:11:05,958 --> 00:11:08,500
What's wrong?! What happened?!

202
00:11:08,583 --> 00:11:09,541
[gasps]

203
00:11:09,625 --> 00:11:11,083
[INKARMAT groans weakly]

204
00:11:12,291 --> 00:11:15,708
When Wilk was...
When he was shot...

205
00:11:15,791 --> 00:11:17,041
[BOTH gasp]

206
00:11:19,250 --> 00:11:22,000
[INKARMAT]
Kiroranke gave someone a signal.

207
00:11:22,083 --> 00:11:23,375
I saw him myself.

208
00:11:24,583 --> 00:11:26,125
Kiroranke did what?

209
00:11:27,208 --> 00:11:30,125
[TSURUMI]
Ah. Private Genjirou Tanigaki.

210
00:11:32,125 --> 00:11:33,625
[laughing menacingly]

211
00:11:35,708 --> 00:11:37,083
[SHIRAISHI]
This must be the spare ship.

212
00:11:37,166 --> 00:11:39,083
That's my guess, anyway.

213
00:11:39,166 --> 00:11:40,625
We can just wait for them here.

214
00:11:40,708 --> 00:11:42,125
-[rustling]
-Huh?

215
00:11:45,041 --> 00:11:46,125
Hey.

216
00:11:46,208 --> 00:11:47,875
Isn't Inkarmat with you?

217
00:11:47,958 --> 00:11:49,500
Have you really not
figured out yet

218
00:11:49,583 --> 00:11:52,166
why the Seventh was able
to track everything we did?

219
00:11:52,250 --> 00:11:53,458
Think about it.

220
00:11:53,541 --> 00:11:55,500
That woman was the reason.

221
00:11:55,583 --> 00:11:57,791
We can't take her with us.

222
00:11:57,875 --> 00:11:59,083
[gasps, sighs]

223
00:12:00,333 --> 00:12:01,500
[OGATA]
Get the boat ready.

224
00:12:01,583 --> 00:12:02,875
We're leaving.

225
00:12:02,958 --> 00:12:06,000
Tanigaki just got caught
by Tsurumi and his men.

226
00:12:06,083 --> 00:12:07,416
What about the others?

227
00:12:13,583 --> 00:12:15,416
I got close to see
if I could help out,

228
00:12:15,500 --> 00:12:18,208
but both of them
were already dead.

229
00:12:18,291 --> 00:12:20,458
♪

230
00:12:59,875 --> 00:13:03,000
[TSURUMI]
So, Immortal Sugimoto.

231
00:13:03,083 --> 00:13:06,416
How does it feel to be missing
a part of your brain?

232
00:13:06,500 --> 00:13:09,416
You know this makes us
brain-damage buddies, don't you?

233
00:13:10,583 --> 00:13:12,958
I can't believe you were
once a great doctor.

234
00:13:13,041 --> 00:13:14,583
You're a murderer.

235
00:13:14,666 --> 00:13:18,291
There's a thin line between
genius and insanity, but...

236
00:13:18,375 --> 00:13:20,166
I've done many
cranial surgeries.

237
00:13:20,250 --> 00:13:23,208
My little torture hobby has been
a great way to learn.

238
00:13:23,291 --> 00:13:25,250
I'd cut out tiny bits
of their brain,

239
00:13:25,333 --> 00:13:27,375
then they'd watch
while I fried it up and eat it.

240
00:13:27,458 --> 00:13:29,333
Right there in front of them.

241
00:13:29,416 --> 00:13:30,916
With ginger soy.

242
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:32,875
[slurps]

243
00:13:35,916 --> 00:13:39,875
Anyway, only someone with
Sugimoto's capacity for recovery

244
00:13:39,958 --> 00:13:41,708
could've survived that.

245
00:13:41,791 --> 00:13:44,250
Inkarmat is the one
who's really in danger.

246
00:13:44,333 --> 00:13:46,875
If you wanna ask her anything,
do it now.

247
00:13:48,041 --> 00:13:50,083
Kiroranke and his partners...

248
00:13:51,208 --> 00:13:53,833
they must've gone to Sakhalin.

249
00:13:53,916 --> 00:13:56,416
♪

250
00:13:59,916 --> 00:14:01,583
We'll have to change ships
at the port.

251
00:14:03,166 --> 00:14:05,166
Get it together.

252
00:14:05,250 --> 00:14:06,791
Come on, Asirpa.

253
00:14:08,958 --> 00:14:10,083
[INKARMAT]
I wish I could've heard

254
00:14:10,166 --> 00:14:11,875
what sort of shot
had killed them.

255
00:14:13,708 --> 00:14:14,875
They were drowned out

256
00:14:14,958 --> 00:14:16,625
by the roar
of all those star shells.

257
00:14:16,708 --> 00:14:18,791
So I couldn't quite hear them.

258
00:14:18,875 --> 00:14:20,166
[door thuds]

259
00:14:20,250 --> 00:14:21,541
[SUGIMOTO] Only Ogata
could've made that shot.

260
00:14:21,625 --> 00:14:23,708
You all know it's true.

261
00:14:23,791 --> 00:14:25,875
-[grunting]
-[laughs]

262
00:14:25,958 --> 00:14:28,000
[SUGIMOTO]
Soon as it hit me,

263
00:14:28,083 --> 00:14:29,375
I felt him there.

264
00:14:29,458 --> 00:14:30,708
[gunshot]

265
00:14:31,833 --> 00:14:34,500
[KIRORANKE] Was it really
necessary to shoot Sugimoto?

266
00:14:35,875 --> 00:14:37,291
[OGATA] In the moment
right after we learned

267
00:14:37,375 --> 00:14:39,041
Nopperabo was her father,

268
00:14:39,125 --> 00:14:42,375
he and Sugimoto exchanged
a few words.

269
00:14:42,458 --> 00:14:44,666
Who can say whether
it was the location of the gold

270
00:14:44,750 --> 00:14:47,916
or the key to cracking some code
only Asirpa knows?

271
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,625
Or, hey, maybe it was about you.

272
00:14:52,916 --> 00:14:56,000
Anyway, the bastard might
still be alive, you know.

273
00:14:56,083 --> 00:14:57,750
And with Asirpa taken away
from him,

274
00:14:57,833 --> 00:14:59,500
I'd imagine
the Immortal Sugimoto

275
00:14:59,583 --> 00:15:01,333
is probably really pissed off.

276
00:15:02,583 --> 00:15:05,791
I'm gonna murder
Ogata and Kiroranke both.

277
00:15:05,875 --> 00:15:10,291
Look at Kazuo Hemni
and Tetsuzou Nihei.

278
00:15:10,375 --> 00:15:13,500
You did such a good job
keeping them soft and supple.

279
00:15:13,583 --> 00:15:15,041
Yeah, thanks.

280
00:15:15,125 --> 00:15:17,958
So what proves Kiroranke's
group made it to Sakhalin?

281
00:15:20,541 --> 00:15:23,291
Hold on!
I just saw you up on the roof!

282
00:15:23,375 --> 00:15:25,458
Here, you take Asirpa!

283
00:15:25,541 --> 00:15:27,041
This woman is dangerous!

284
00:15:27,125 --> 00:15:28,958
Don't believe him, Asirpa!

285
00:15:29,041 --> 00:15:30,291
I saw Kiroranke--

286
00:15:30,375 --> 00:15:31,250
[INKARMAT groans]

287
00:15:31,333 --> 00:15:32,791
Shut your mouth.

288
00:15:34,166 --> 00:15:35,541
[INKARMAT]
You'll pay for killing Wilk.

289
00:15:35,625 --> 00:15:37,500
[BOTH grunting]

290
00:15:40,750 --> 00:15:41,666
[BOTH grunt]

291
00:15:42,791 --> 00:15:44,041
[groaning]

292
00:15:46,625 --> 00:15:47,875
[gasps]

293
00:15:47,958 --> 00:15:48,833
I didn't mean to.

294
00:15:48,916 --> 00:15:50,833
-[grunting]
-[groaning]

295
00:15:52,916 --> 00:15:54,125
[KIRORANKE]
Let it go!

296
00:15:55,375 --> 00:15:56,541
[groaning]

297
00:15:57,958 --> 00:15:59,291
If we don't act,

298
00:15:59,375 --> 00:16:01,666
the bigger countries
will simply swallow us up.

299
00:16:01,750 --> 00:16:04,583
[weakly]
But why did Wilk have to die?

300
00:16:04,666 --> 00:16:07,125
Was that really necessary
for your revolt?

301
00:16:07,208 --> 00:16:08,833
Wilk changed.

302
00:16:08,916 --> 00:16:11,375
He wasn't the same man,

303
00:16:11,458 --> 00:16:14,000
because the plan had always been
to tell our old comrades

304
00:16:14,083 --> 00:16:15,208
where that gold was hidden.

305
00:16:15,291 --> 00:16:16,166
[door opens]

306
00:16:18,916 --> 00:16:20,875
[TSURUMI]
After killing the seven Ainu,

307
00:16:20,958 --> 00:16:23,083
Nopperabo took a small portion
of the gold

308
00:16:23,166 --> 00:16:24,833
and headed to Sakhalin.

309
00:16:24,916 --> 00:16:27,166
He was captured
on his way there.

310
00:16:27,250 --> 00:16:29,375
His information was reliable.

311
00:16:29,458 --> 00:16:31,458
He was planning to bring in
their main forces,

312
00:16:31,541 --> 00:16:33,541
from what I understand.

313
00:16:33,625 --> 00:16:35,083
As for Kiroranke,

314
00:16:35,166 --> 00:16:37,333
since he has Asirpa,
the critical key

315
00:16:37,416 --> 00:16:38,541
in his possession,

316
00:16:38,625 --> 00:16:40,291
I imagine he'll likely
try to meet up

317
00:16:40,375 --> 00:16:43,416
with his former guerilla friends
in the far east.

318
00:16:43,500 --> 00:16:45,875
If those partisans
get their hands on Asirpa,

319
00:16:45,958 --> 00:16:47,916
we'll have a problem.

320
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:50,500
I've got to go get her back.

321
00:16:50,583 --> 00:16:52,958
You'll take me to Sakhalin.

322
00:16:53,041 --> 00:16:54,708
That's the only way.

323
00:16:54,791 --> 00:16:56,916
She wouldn't trust you alone.

324
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:58,375
[TANIGAKI]
I'll go, too.

325
00:16:58,458 --> 00:17:00,458
Sugimoto's telling you
the truth.

326
00:17:00,541 --> 00:17:02,666
She only trusts us now.

327
00:17:02,750 --> 00:17:03,750
[SUGIMOTO]
You're sure?

328
00:17:05,375 --> 00:17:06,958
I'll come back.

329
00:17:07,041 --> 00:17:10,333
So stay alive
or I'll never forgive you.

330
00:17:10,416 --> 00:17:12,041
[INKARMAT chuckles softly]

331
00:17:12,125 --> 00:17:15,250
What are we doing?!
We have to go get Asirpa back!

332
00:17:15,333 --> 00:17:17,291
Asirpa!

333
00:17:17,375 --> 00:17:18,583
Looks like you took
a little nibble

334
00:17:18,666 --> 00:17:20,166
off my brain, huh?

335
00:17:20,250 --> 00:17:22,416
Well, here's
the unfortunate thing.

336
00:17:22,500 --> 00:17:24,833
I still have some clean-up work
to do at Abashiri,

337
00:17:24,916 --> 00:17:27,083
so I can't leave quite yet.

338
00:17:27,166 --> 00:17:29,250
So for now, we're going to send
a small force

339
00:17:29,333 --> 00:17:31,416
ahead of the rest of us.

340
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:33,875
Sergeant Tsukishima
and Lieutenant Koito.

341
00:17:33,958 --> 00:17:35,458
You'll go along with them,
as well.

342
00:17:35,541 --> 00:17:37,916
[screams]

343
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:40,083
-[whispering]
-He's upset.

344
00:17:40,166 --> 00:17:43,125
"Why do I have to leave you,
Lieutenant Tsurumi?" he asks.

345
00:17:43,208 --> 00:17:46,166
It's actually a request
from your father, Admiral Koito.

346
00:17:46,250 --> 00:17:47,166
[KOITO groans]

347
00:17:49,708 --> 00:17:52,166
♪

348
00:17:58,708 --> 00:18:00,125
[USHIYAMA]
The Seventh knew exactly

349
00:18:00,208 --> 00:18:02,041
what we were doing at Abashiri.

350
00:18:02,125 --> 00:18:04,083
They were very well informed.

351
00:18:04,166 --> 00:18:06,833
So old man Nagakura
and the others at the kotan

352
00:18:06,916 --> 00:18:08,375
might've been captured.

353
00:18:08,458 --> 00:18:10,791
[HIJIKATA] In two or three days
things will calm down,

354
00:18:10,875 --> 00:18:13,625
and there'll be fewer soldiers
swarming the place.

355
00:18:13,708 --> 00:18:15,666
So we'll just wait until then.

356
00:18:20,333 --> 00:18:21,916
[USHIYAMA]
Who made this?

357
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:23,625
Inudou?

358
00:18:23,708 --> 00:18:24,958
[HIJIKATA]
From the look of this,

359
00:18:25,041 --> 00:18:26,791
it seems like he was
gathering information

360
00:18:26,875 --> 00:18:29,666
about the escaped prisoners
to lure me here.

361
00:18:31,250 --> 00:18:34,666
Some of this is definitely
information we don't have.

362
00:18:34,750 --> 00:18:38,208
So, if the skins we had are in
Lieutenant Tsurumi's hands now,

363
00:18:38,291 --> 00:18:40,916
then what's our plan
going forward?

364
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:42,791
We've got to find at least
one of the others

365
00:18:42,875 --> 00:18:45,250
so we can stop him
from breaking the code.

366
00:18:45,333 --> 00:18:46,833
I thought Ahbashiri
had turned out

367
00:18:46,916 --> 00:18:48,458
to be a big waste of time,

368
00:18:48,541 --> 00:18:51,958
but now we seem to have found
a small glimmer of light.

369
00:18:52,041 --> 00:18:53,500
We're leaving here
and heading south

370
00:18:53,583 --> 00:18:54,958
as soon as possible.

371
00:19:10,375 --> 00:19:11,500
[ADMIRAL KOITO]
Sugimoto.

372
00:19:14,166 --> 00:19:15,875
So you really wanna
send your kid

373
00:19:15,958 --> 00:19:17,666
on a big adventure, do you?

374
00:19:17,750 --> 00:19:19,166
There's a very high probability

375
00:19:19,250 --> 00:19:21,666
that boy won't come back
to you alive.

376
00:19:21,750 --> 00:19:24,958
Oh, don't worry,
he's fully prepared to die.

377
00:19:25,041 --> 00:19:28,250
My son will be a great leader
of men someday.

378
00:19:28,333 --> 00:19:30,750
And a leader often
has to take responsibility

379
00:19:30,833 --> 00:19:32,375
for many young lives.

380
00:19:34,666 --> 00:19:36,250
I need him to be the sort of man

381
00:19:36,333 --> 00:19:38,541
who's worthy
of that kind of duty.

382
00:19:39,833 --> 00:19:42,541
When Lieutenant General Hanazawa
committed seppuku,

383
00:19:42,625 --> 00:19:45,250
he sent me a letter directly.

384
00:19:45,333 --> 00:19:49,083
His son, Yuusaku, had died
on the front lines, you see.

385
00:19:49,166 --> 00:19:51,791
Upholding the honor
of his foolish father.

386
00:19:52,958 --> 00:19:56,000
The terrible war
that our generation started,

387
00:19:56,083 --> 00:19:59,791
has been responsible for sending
so many of our sons into battle.

388
00:20:00,791 --> 00:20:03,375
If I dare to keep
my own son from danger,

389
00:20:03,458 --> 00:20:06,125
how could I bear to look
into the eyes of any parent

390
00:20:06,208 --> 00:20:08,333
who's lost so much?

391
00:20:08,416 --> 00:20:09,708
It seems to me

392
00:20:09,791 --> 00:20:13,791
Nopperabo just was the same,
about his child.

393
00:20:13,875 --> 00:20:16,041
If he was going to ask
the Ainu people

394
00:20:16,125 --> 00:20:17,666
to risk their lives,

395
00:20:17,750 --> 00:20:18,958
first he had to be willing

396
00:20:19,041 --> 00:20:21,833
to send his own daughter
into battle.

397
00:20:21,916 --> 00:20:25,166
I can understand why you'd
disapprove of his intentions,

398
00:20:25,250 --> 00:20:27,833
but I don't think he raised her
just to be used.

399
00:20:33,291 --> 00:20:34,958
♪

400
00:20:36,958 --> 00:20:38,875
[gasps]

401
00:20:38,958 --> 00:20:40,041
[ASIRPA]
Sugimoto.

402
00:20:41,250 --> 00:20:42,916
I'm here.

403
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:44,291
But I thought...

404
00:20:44,375 --> 00:20:45,625
Aren't you...

405
00:20:49,666 --> 00:20:51,250
Asirpa, I am so sorry

406
00:20:51,333 --> 00:20:53,291
I couldn't get you
to your father.

407
00:20:56,500 --> 00:20:57,833
I broke my promise.

408
00:20:59,208 --> 00:21:00,541
Forgive me.

409
00:21:01,916 --> 00:21:03,125
So, aca...

410
00:21:04,833 --> 00:21:05,833
left on his journey?

411
00:21:07,708 --> 00:21:08,791
I'm sorry.

412
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:13,375
Just hang on.

413
00:21:13,458 --> 00:21:15,416
I will always come for you!

414
00:21:15,500 --> 00:21:18,333
Asirpa, do you hear me?!
I swear, I'm coming!

415
00:21:20,791 --> 00:21:22,583
♪

416
00:21:22,666 --> 00:21:24,666
This has to be a dream.

417
00:21:24,750 --> 00:21:27,166
So if the kamuy are trying
to tell me something,

418
00:21:27,250 --> 00:21:30,458
then it must have
some kind of special meaning.

419
00:21:30,541 --> 00:21:32,250
-[SUGIMOTO] No!
-[gasps]

420
00:21:32,333 --> 00:21:33,708
[SUGIMOTO]
Asirpa!

421
00:21:33,791 --> 00:21:35,166
This isn't the kamuy!

422
00:21:35,250 --> 00:21:37,125
It really is me!

423
00:21:37,208 --> 00:21:38,083
[gasps]

424
00:21:39,791 --> 00:21:41,000
[SUGIMOTO]
I'm alive!

425
00:21:41,083 --> 00:21:43,000
And there's so much
I wanna tell you,

426
00:21:43,083 --> 00:21:44,791
so just hang on!

427
00:21:49,166 --> 00:21:50,583
You okay?

428
00:21:50,666 --> 00:21:51,833
Have a bad dream?

429
00:21:51,916 --> 00:21:53,083
-Hmm?
-Hmm?

430
00:21:56,333 --> 00:21:58,166
We need to get to Sakhalin.

431
00:21:58,250 --> 00:21:59,458
This route is best.

432
00:22:03,750 --> 00:22:05,625
I dreamt about Sugimoto.

433
00:22:05,708 --> 00:22:07,291
Huh?

434
00:22:07,375 --> 00:22:09,250
[ASIRPA]
He said he was coming for me.

435
00:22:10,708 --> 00:22:13,541
Hey, it might
really be true. It's...

436
00:22:13,625 --> 00:22:15,916
I can't seem to
imagine him dying, you know?

437
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:18,041
What are you even saying?

438
00:22:18,125 --> 00:22:19,750
Of course he isn't dead.

439
00:22:21,541 --> 00:22:22,541
[chuckles softly]

440
00:22:25,875 --> 00:22:27,750
Just hold on, Asirpa.

441
00:22:29,125 --> 00:22:30,875
After all...

442
00:22:30,958 --> 00:22:31,875
After all...

443
00:22:33,083 --> 00:22:34,041
I'm Immortal Sugimoto.

444
00:22:34,125 --> 00:22:35,500
[ASIRPA]
He's Immortal Sugimoto.

